node.text: On the coast of Portugal, Gordon Ramsay visits one of the most unique vineyards on the planet where the vines grow in the sand. A new season of Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted airs Monday, May 31 at 9/8c.

node.title: Gordon Ramsay: Uncharted – A Vineyard in the Sand

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of one or more people, sky and skyscraper.

node.text: Photo by @MichaelGeorge / Visitors at the Edge NYC look at the city more than 1,100 feet (336 meters) below. This corner is not for the faint of heart, as it floats freely above the Hudson Yards neighborhood of Manhattan. The views—of Central Park, downtown, all three bridges to Brooklyn, and even New Jersey—are worth the slight vertigo. For more photos and writing from my travels, follow along @MichaelGeorge. #edgenyc #hudsonyards #nyc #newyorkcity #Manhattan

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 03, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / Visitors lie like lizards in the sun at Fortescue Falls in Karijini National Park. While traveling through the park in the winter, the temperatures can still create days that feel like summer. Winter is the prime time to venture through the desert of Western Australia, as the summer brings the soaring heat and the wet season, which often makes many places inaccessible.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 02, 2021. May be an image of nature and mountain.

node.text:
Photo by @amivitale / Reteti Elephant Sanctuary (@r.e.s.c.u.e) keepers take Shaba and Pokot to walk in the Namunyak Wildlife Conservancy in northern Kenya. Rescued as young calves, Shaba and Pokot were cared for by the dedicated team at Reteti until they were ready to return to the wild. The elephants were transferred to nearby Sera Conservancy for their soft release back to the wild on November 16, 2019.
Follow @amivitale for more extraordinary stories of people and wildlife coexisting. @kenyawildlifeservice @thephotosociety #protectelephants #elephants #stoppoaching #kenya #empathyiseverything

node.text: Photo by @EnricSala / The Cocos Islands in Costa Rica are sometimes called "the little Galápagos” because of their rich species biodiversity. While diving on a @natgeopristineseas expedition, we routinely swam with whitetip sharks, hammerhead sharks, and this speckled filter feeder, the whale shark. For more from our expeditions around the globe, follow @natgeopristineseas.

node.text: Photo by Eduardo Teixeira de Sousa @edtsousa / Worse Things Happen at Sea. A winter storm beats the shore in Porto, Portugal. Congratulations to Eduardo on becoming the August Your Shot Photographer of the Month! @natgeoyourshot #YourShotPhotographer

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 02, 2021. May be an image of nature and body of water.

node.text:
Photo by @sarahyltonphoto / A hazy winter sunset began to form in Patna, in India's Bihar state, as a fisherman delicately wove his wooden boat along the ghats of the Ganges River. I was on assignment for @natgeo, and my main camera suddenly stopped releasing the shutter (granted, it dates to the 1950s). I had decided to test my backup camera, a medium format I had barely used. As I fumbled with it, I was certain I had missed this scene and the rest that followed. But that's the beauty (and stress) of film: The images that are meant to come to life always do. 
For more travel stories, follow me @sarahyltonphoto. #india #ganges #mediumformat

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 02, 2021. May be an image of bird, lake and nature.

node.text: Photo by Michael Yamashita @yamashitaphoto // Sponsored by @nationalpark_japan // The 34 national parks in Japan welcome over 300 million visitors a year—human visitors, that is. Because many parks are along the pathways of migratory birds, they’re also great places to find actual “snowbirds,” like these whooper swans heading south for the winter from Siberia. I photographed them at Akan-Mashu National Park in Hokkaido, where I shot my first story for National Geographic. These majestic swans fly in every winter, landing at Lake Kussharo. Though the caldera lake is almost completely frozen, the swans find balmy water near the hot springs along the banks. // Discover where nature and culture live as one in the national parks of Japan. #nationalparksjp

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 01, 2021. May be an image of coast, nature and ocean.

node.text: Photo by @krystlejwright / The remote and rugged coastline of Western Australia—20,788 kilometers (12,917 miles) long—is a vast playground to explore. One particular place that attracts tourists in the winter is the Ningaloo Reef. Visitors can see phenomenal wildlife such as whale sharks and manta rays and surf world-class waves.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 01, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
Photo by @daisygilardini / A polar bear sniffs the air, looking for seals on the summer pack ice. The Arctic is warming three times faster than the rest of the planet, causing the sea ice to melt. In several regions around the Arctic, this is reducing the time polar bears have to hunt seals, increasing their fasting period and forcing them to rely on their fat stores for longer amounts of time. If the Arctic continues to warm at the current rate, we will see fewer polar bears in fewer places across the Arctic, making them more vulnerable to extinction.
Follow me @daisygilardini for more images and behind-the-scenes stories. #climatechange #polarbear #Svalbard

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 01, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text: Photo by Keith Ladzinski @ladzinski / Antelope Canyon is one of the most photographed canyons in the American Southwest. It's easy to see why as you walk along the sandy floor among the tightly carved walls of Navajo Sandstone.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by National Geographic Travel on September 01, 2021. May be a closeup.

node.text:
Photo by @bertiegregory / This Atlantic puffin's bill is packed full of sand eels. Puffins breed on land but fish at sea, so being able to carry multiple prey at once is key to efficiently—and therefore successfully—raising a puffling (puffin chick). The busy summer breeding colonies have now emptied out, and the puffins will spend the rest of the year at sea. Next spring the adults will return to land to start the whole process again. Meanwhile, the pufflings will stay at sea for three to five years before returning to land to raise their own chicks. 
Follow @bertiegregory for more wildlife adventures! #puffin #britishwildlife #cute #fishing #wildlifephotography
